<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06242116 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06242116 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Assemblywoman Jackie Speier; ... Author of resolution  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  CALIFORNIA; CONGRESS; ABORTION; PRODUCT; LAW; CONTROVERSY  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  An Assembly committee Wednesday approved legislation that would urge thefederal government to support research into RU-486, the French abortion pill.;  But opponents refused to allow Assemblywoman Jackie Speier, D-South SanFrancisco, to have the full Assembly vote on her resolution.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  California News  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  ABORTION PILL FUNDING DEBATED  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  California News.  </MEMO><TEXT>     Her measure, AJR 40, would ask the president and Congress to supportresearch into the controversial French drug.;   The resolution says RU-486 hasbeen shown in Europe to be a safe and effective way to terminate earlypregnancies and also is a promising treatment for breast and brain cancer andother conditions.;   The Ways and Means Committee voted 12-4 to send themeasure to the Assembly floor.;   &quot;It puts us on record as in favor ofresearch,&quot; Speier said. &quot;We can't stick our heads in the sand and allow theMoral Majority, the right-to-life community, as small as it is, to curtailresearch.&quot;;   However, Assemblyman Bill Baker, R-Walnut Creek, said, &quot;We'regoing on record in support of research for a drug that is primarily used toterminate pregnancies between the fifth and seventh week. Some of us believelife begins at the beginning.&quot;;   Speier later in the day tried to bring theresolution up on the Assembly floor, but opponents refused to allow her. Shesaid she would try again today.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Sacramento  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910829  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  August  </MONTH><PG.COL>  2E  </PG.COL><PU